#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:1
msgid "Project: Async MLP Pipeline"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:3
msgid ""
"You have learned how to define kernels, move data, compose operations with "
"combinators, and schedule work across streams. Time to put it all together."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:6
msgid ""
"This chapter walks through `async_mlp` — the most complete example in the "
"cuda-oxide repository — from the first `use` statement to the final `[ReLU "
"OK]` on stdout. By the end you will have built a multi-kernel GPU pipeline "
"that processes four batches concurrently, using every async pattern in the "
"toolkit. If you have been reading the chapters sequentially, consider this "
"the final boss."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:14
msgid ""
"The [Concurrent Execution](../async-programming/concurrent-execution.md) "
"chapter covers the *concepts* behind concurrent pipelines in depth. This "
"chapter focuses on the *code* — a complete, buildable project you can run, "
"modify, and profile."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:22
msgid "What we are building"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:24
msgid "A toy **multi-layer perceptron (MLP) forward pass** on the GPU:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:26
msgid ""
"input [64×64]  ──►  GEMM(input, W0)  ──►  hidden [64×64]\n"
"                                              │\n"
"                            MatVec(hidden, W1) ──►  output [64]\n"
"                                                       │\n"
"                                                 ReLU(output) ──►  result "
"[64]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:34
msgid ""
"Three kernels, four stages (including the final device-to-host copy), four "
"batches, four CUDA streams, one shared set of weights, and zero host threads "
"sitting around waiting. Here is the big picture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:42
msgid ""
"Four MLP forward passes running concurrently. Shared weights are uploaded "
"once as `Arc<DeviceBox>` and cloned cheaply into each batch. The round-robin "
"scheduler distributes batches across four streams, and the staggered "
"pipelines overlap on the GPU timeline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:48
msgid ""
"The sequential approach processes one batch at a time — four times the work, "
"four times the wait. The concurrent approach overlaps them: if the GPU has "
"spare SMs, you finish in roughly the time of a single batch plus a small "
"stagger. Not a bad return on a handful of `Arc::clone()` calls."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:55
msgid "Project structure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:57
msgid ""
"The example lives at `crates/rustc-codegen-cuda/examples/async_mlp/` and is "
"a standalone Cargo workspace member:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:60
msgid ""
"async_mlp/\n"
"├── Cargo.toml        ← dependencies: cuda-device, cuda-core, cuda-async, "
"tokio\n"
"└── src/\n"
"    └── main.rs       ← kernels + host code, single file\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:67
msgid ""
"Everything — device kernels and host orchestration — lives in one file. The "
"`#[kernel]` attribute tells the compiler which functions become PTX; the "
"rest compiles as normal Rust. No separate `.cu` files, no header gymnastics, "
"no build-system split personality."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:72
msgid "Dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:74
msgid "The `Cargo.toml` pulls in exactly the crates we need:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:76
msgid ""
"[dependencies]\n"
"cuda-device   = { path = \"../../../cuda-device\" }       # #[kernel], "
"DisjointSlice, thread::*\n"
"cuda-core = { path = \"../../../cuda-core\" }      # CudaModule, "
"LaunchConfig\n"
"cuda-async  = { path = \"../../../cuda-async\" }       # DeviceOperation, "
"zip!, and_then, spawn\n"
"tokio       = { version = \"1\", features = [\"rt\", \"macros\"] }\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:84
msgid ""
"`cuda-device` provides the device-side API (intrinsics, safe mutable "
"slices). `cuda-core` handles module loading and launch configuration. `cuda-"
"async` provides the `DeviceOperation` graph, combinators, and the stream-"
"pool scheduler. `tokio` is the host async runtime that polls the futures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:92
msgid "The GPU kernels"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:94
msgid ""
"These three functions are compiled to PTX by `rustc-codegen-cuda`. They "
"never execute on the host — the `#[kernel]` attribute renames each one to "
"`cuda_oxide_kernel_<hash>_<name>` so the codegen backend can identify and "
"extract them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:99
msgid "sgemm_naive — matrix multiply"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:101
msgid ""
"use cuda_device::{kernel, thread, DisjointSlice};\n"
"\n"
"use cuda_device::thread::Runtime2DIndex;\n"
"\n"
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn sgemm_naive(\n"
"    m: u32, n: u32, k: u32,\n"
"    alpha: f32, a: &[f32], b: &[f32],\n"
"    beta: f32, mut c: DisjointSlice<f32, Runtime2DIndex>,\n"
") {\n"
"    let n_sz = n as usize;\n"
"    let row = thread::index_2d_row();\n"
"    let col = thread::index_2d_col();\n"
"\n"
"    // SAFETY: every thread sees the same `n_sz` (same kernel arg).\n"
"    if let Some(c_idx) = unsafe { thread::index_2d_runtime(n_sz) } {\n"
"        // col < n_sz guaranteed by `Some` -- no manual check needed\n"
"        if row < m as usize {\n"
"            let k_sz = k as usize;\n"
"            let mut sum = 0.0f32;\n"
"            let mut i = 0usize;\n"
"            while i < k_sz {\n"
"                sum = sum + a[row * k_sz + i] * b[i * n_sz + col];\n"
"                i = i + 1;\n"
"            }\n"
"            if let Some(c_elem) = c.get_mut(c_idx) {\n"
"                *c_elem = alpha * sum + beta * (*c_elem);\n"
"            }\n"
"        }\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:135
msgid ""
"Each thread computes one element of the output matrix. The 2D thread index "
"maps directly to the (row, col) position. `DisjointSlice` checks bounds and "
"requires the matching index-space type. The remaining proof is explicit: "
"every thread uses the same runtime stride, Z is inactive, and the raw 2D "
"launch shape matches the kernel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:142
msgid ""
"This is intentionally a *naive* GEMM — one thread, one element, no shared "
"memory tiling, no coalescing tricks. A production GEMM would use the "
"techniques from the [Shared Memory](../advanced/shared-memory-and-"
"synchronization.md) chapter. But for demonstrating async composition, "
"correctness beats performance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:149
msgid "matvec_naive — matrix-vector product"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:151
msgid ""
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn matvec_naive(\n"
"    _m: u32, n: u32,\n"
"    mat: &[f32], vec_in: &[f32],\n"
"    mut vec_out: DisjointSlice<f32>,\n"
") {\n"
"    let row = thread::index_1d();\n"
"    if let Some(out_elem) = vec_out.get_mut(row) {\n"
"        let n_sz = n as usize;\n"
"        let mut sum = 0.0f32;\n"
"        let mut j = 0usize;\n"
"        while j < n_sz {\n"
"            sum = sum + mat[row.get() * n_sz + j] * vec_in[j];\n"
"            j = j + 1;\n"
"        }\n"
"        *out_elem = sum;\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:172
msgid ""
"One thread per output element, one-dimensional indexing. The `_m` parameter "
"is unused but keeps the calling convention consistent with BLAS-style "
"interfaces."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:176
msgid "relu — activation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:178
msgid ""
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn relu(input: &[f32], mut output: DisjointSlice<f32>) {\n"
"    let idx = thread::index_1d();\n"
"    if let Some(out_elem) = output.get_mut(idx) {\n"
"        let val = input[idx.get()];\n"
"        *out_elem = if val > 0.0f32 { val } else { 0.0f32 };\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:189
msgid ""
"Elementwise `max(0, x)`. In the pipeline, `input` and `output` point to the "
"same buffer — a perfectly valid in-place pattern since each thread reads and "
"writes the same index and the launch is 1D."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:193
msgid "What to notice"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:195
msgid "A few patterns that recur across all three kernels:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:141
msgid "Pattern"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:141
msgid "What it does"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:141
msgid "`thread::index_1d()` / `index_2d::<S>()`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:141
msgid "Computes the global thread index from block/grid dimensions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:141
msgid "`DisjointSlice<f32>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:141
msgid ""
"Bounds-checked mutable output; launch geometry completes the uniqueness proof"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:141
msgid "`if let Some(elem) = slice.get_mut(idx)`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:141
msgid "Bounds check that silences threads beyond the data size"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:141
msgid "`while` loops instead of `for`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:141
msgid ""
"Stylistic choice — `for` loops with ranges also work on device, but `while` "
"makes the loop bounds explicit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:206
msgid "Bridging host and device"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:208
msgid ""
"Three helper functions wrap raw CUDA driver calls into `DeviceOperation` "
"values. They use `with_context` to receive the scheduler's stream at "
"execution time — not at the call site. This is the key insight: you build "
"the recipe now, the scheduler picks the stream later."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:213
msgid "h2d — host to device"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:215
msgid ""
"fn h2d(host_data: Vec<f32>) -> impl DeviceOperation<Output = "
"DeviceBox<[f32]>> {\n"
"    device_operation::with_context(move |ctx| {\n"
"        let stream = ctx.get_cuda_stream();\n"
"        let n = host_data.len();\n"
"        let num_bytes = n * mem::size_of::<f32>();\n"
"        unsafe {\n"
"            let dptr = malloc_async(stream.cu_stream(), num_bytes)."
"unwrap();\n"
"            memcpy_htod_async(dptr, host_data.as_ptr(), num_bytes, stream."
"cu_stream())\n"
"                .unwrap();\n"
"            value(DeviceBox::from_raw_parts(dptr, n, ctx.get_device_id()))\n"
"        }\n"
"    })\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:231
msgid ""
"The `host_data` vector is captured by `move`. The closure runs when the "
"scheduler executes the operation — at that point it has a real CUDA stream. "
"`malloc_async` and `memcpy_htod_async` are stream-ordered, so the allocation "
"and copy are serialized on the scheduler's chosen stream."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:236
msgid "zeros — zero-initialized device buffer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:238
msgid ""
"fn zeros(n: usize) -> impl DeviceOperation<Output = DeviceBox<[f32]>> {\n"
"    device_operation::with_context(move |ctx| {\n"
"        let stream = ctx.get_cuda_stream();\n"
"        let num_bytes = n * mem::size_of::<f32>();\n"
"        unsafe {\n"
"            let dptr = malloc_async(stream.cu_stream(), num_bytes)."
"unwrap();\n"
"            memset_d8_async(dptr, 0, num_bytes, stream.cu_stream())."
"unwrap();\n"
"            value(DeviceBox::from_raw_parts(dptr, n, ctx.get_device_id()))\n"
"        }\n"
"    })\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:252
msgid ""
"Same pattern as `h2d`, but `memset_d8_async` instead of `memcpy`. The GEMM "
"kernel uses `beta = 0.0` so the initial contents do not matter, but zeroing "
"is defensive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:256
msgid "d2h — device to host"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:258
msgid ""
"fn d2h(dev: DeviceBox<[f32]>) -> impl DeviceOperation<Output = Vec<f32>> {\n"
"    device_operation::with_context(move |ctx| {\n"
"        let stream = ctx.get_cuda_stream();\n"
"        let n = dev.len();\n"
"        let num_bytes = n * mem::size_of::<f32>();\n"
"        let mut host = vec![0.0f32; n];\n"
"        unsafe {\n"
"            memcpy_dtoh_async(\n"
"                host.as_mut_ptr(), dev.cu_deviceptr(),\n"
"                num_bytes, stream.cu_stream(),\n"
"            ).unwrap();\n"
"        }\n"
"        let _ = &dev;\n"
"        value(host)\n"
"    })\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:277
msgid ""
"The `let _ = &dev;` line looks like a no-op, but it keeps `dev` alive in the "
"closure until the stream synchronizes. Without it, `dev` would be dropped "
"after the `memcpy_dtoh_async` call but before the stream finishes the copy — "
"a classic use-after-free on the device side."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:284
msgid "Composing the pipeline"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:286
msgid ""
"Each batch is a single `DeviceOperation` built from combinators. No GPU work "
"happens when you assemble it — it is a lazy description of future work. Here "
"is how the pieces fit together:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:294
msgid ""
"The combinator pipeline for a single batch. `zip!` allocates three buffers "
"in parallel. The `and_then` chain sequences GEMM → MatVec → ReLU → D2H, "
"threading device handles through each stage via `value()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:299
msgid "Step 1: Initialize the runtime"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:301
msgid ""
"const DIM: usize = 64;\n"
"const BLOCK: u32 = 16;\n"
"\n"
"#[tokio::main]\n"
"async fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {\n"
"    init_device_contexts(0, 1)?;\n"
"    let module = kernels::load_async(0)?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:311
msgid ""
"`init_device_contexts(0, 1)` sets device 0 as the default and initializes "
"the device context map (capacity 1). The round-robin stream pool is created "
"lazily on first use. The embedded module compiled from our `#[kernel]` "
"functions is loaded once and shared by the typed module handle."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:316
msgid "Step 2: Upload shared weights"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:318
msgid ""
"    let w0_host: Vec<f32> = (0..DIM * DIM)\n"
"        .map(|i| ((i % 7) as f32 - 3.0) * 0.01)\n"
"        .collect();\n"
"    let w1_host: Vec<f32> = (0..DIM)\n"
"        .map(|i| ((i % 5) as f32 - 2.0) * 0.01)\n"
"        .collect();\n"
"\n"
"    let (w0, w1): (Arc<DeviceBox<[f32]>>, Arc<DeviceBox<[f32]>>) =\n"
"        zip!(h2d(w0_host).arc(), h2d(w1_host).arc()).await?;\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:330
msgid ""
"Two independent uploads, bundled with `zip!` so they can share a stream. `."
"arc()` wraps each result in `Arc` — a reference-counted pointer that costs "
"roughly one nanosecond to clone. Four batches, four clones, zero device "
"copies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:335
msgid "Step 3: Build the per-batch pipeline"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:337
msgid ""
"This is where the magic lives. For each batch, we build a four-stage chain:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:339
msgid ""
"    use cuda_async::launch::{AsyncKernelLaunchBuilder, "
"OwnedAsyncKernelLaunch};\n"
"\n"
"    let pipeline = zip!(h2d(batch_data), zeros(DIM * DIM), zeros(DIM))\n"
"        .and_then(move |(input, hidden, output)| {\n"
"            // Stage 1: GEMM — hidden = input @ W0\n"
"            let func = module.load_function(\"sgemm_naive\").unwrap();\n"
"            let mut builder = AsyncKernelLaunchBuilder::new(Arc::"
"new(func));\n"
"            builder.push_args((\n"
"                DIM as u32, DIM as u32, DIM as u32,\n"
"                1.0f32,\n"
"                input.cu_deviceptr(), input.len() as u64,\n"
"                w0.cu_deviceptr(), w0.len() as u64,\n"
"                0.0f32,\n"
"                hidden.cu_deviceptr(), hidden.len() as u64,\n"
"            ));\n"
"            // SAFETY: packet/config match sgemm_naive, the scheduler uses "
"the\n"
"            // module's context, and the owned wrapper retains its "
"allocations.\n"
"            let launch = unsafe { builder.finalize_unchecked(gemm_cfg) };\n"
"            let launch = OwnedAsyncKernelLaunch::new(launch, (input, w0, "
"hidden));\n"
"            launch.and_then(move |(_input, _w0, hidden)| {\n"
"                value((hidden, output, w1, module))\n"
"            })\n"
"        })\n"
"        .and_then(move |(hidden, output, w1, module)| {\n"
"            // Stage 2: MatVec — output = hidden @ W1\n"
"            let func = module.load_function(\"matvec_naive\").unwrap();\n"
"            let mut builder = AsyncKernelLaunchBuilder::new(Arc::"
"new(func));\n"
"            builder.push_args((\n"
"                DIM as u32, DIM as u32,\n"
"                hidden.cu_deviceptr(), hidden.len() as u64,\n"
"                w1.cu_deviceptr(), w1.len() as u64,\n"
"                output.cu_deviceptr(), output.len() as u64,\n"
"            ));\n"
"            // SAFETY: packet/config match matvec_naive, the scheduler uses "
"the\n"
"            // module's context, and the owned wrapper retains its "
"allocations.\n"
"            let launch = unsafe { builder.finalize_unchecked(matvec_cfg) };\n"
"            let launch = OwnedAsyncKernelLaunch::new(launch, (hidden, w1, "
"output));\n"
"            launch.and_then(move |(_hidden, _w1, output)| value((output, "
"module)))\n"
"        })\n"
"        .and_then(move |(output, module)| {\n"
"            // Stage 3: ReLU — result = max(0, output)\n"
"            let func = module.load_function(\"relu\").unwrap();\n"
"            let relu_out: DeviceBox<[f32]> = output;\n"
"            let mut builder = AsyncKernelLaunchBuilder::new(Arc::"
"new(func));\n"
"            builder.push_args((\n"
"                relu_out.cu_deviceptr(), relu_out.len() as u64,\n"
"                relu_out.cu_deviceptr(), relu_out.len() as u64,\n"
"            ));\n"
"            // SAFETY: packet/config match relu, the scheduler uses the "
"module's\n"
"            // context, and the owned wrapper retains output.\n"
"            let launch = unsafe { builder.finalize_unchecked(relu_cfg) };\n"
"            OwnedAsyncKernelLaunch::new(launch, relu_out)\n"
"        })\n"
"        .and_then(d2h);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:396
msgid "A few things are worth slowing down for:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:398
msgid ""
"**The `value()` baton.** Each `and_then` closure consumes the previous "
"stage's output and returns a `DeviceOperation`. Kernel launches return `()`, "
"so you need `value()` to carry forward the device handles the next stage "
"needs. Think of it as a relay baton — the kernel runs, the baton passes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:403
msgid ""
"**Type annotations.** The deeply nested generics from `zip!` + `and_then` "
"chains exceed Rust's type inference. You will need explicit annotations on "
"closure parameters:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:407
msgid ""
".and_then(move |(hidden, output, w1, module): (\n"
"    DeviceBox<[f32]>,\n"
"    DeviceBox<[f32]>,\n"
"    Arc<DeviceBox<[f32]>>,\n"
"    Arc<CudaModule>,\n"
")| { ... })\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:416
msgid ""
"This is the one ergonomic rough edge. The `Zippable` trait import is also "
"required for `zip!` to work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:419
msgid ""
"**In-place ReLU.** Stage 3 passes `relu_out` as both `input` and `output` to "
"the kernel. Since each thread reads `input[idx]` and writes `output[idx]` at "
"the same index, this is safe — no thread reads another's write."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:423
msgid ""
"**Raw launch boundary.** The builder is inert. `finalize_unchecked` is where "
"the raw packet and geometry become runnable, so each call has a local safety "
"proof. `OwnedAsyncKernelLaunch` keeps its buffers alive. Prefer generated "
"owned-async methods with `PreparedLaunch<K>` when the kernel declares a "
"launch contract."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:429
msgid "Step 4: Spawn and collect"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:431
msgid "    handles.push(tokio::spawn(pipeline.into_future()));\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:435
msgid ""
"`.into_future()` converts the lazy `DeviceOperation` into a `DeviceFuture`. "
"At this point the scheduling policy picks a stream (batch 0 → stream 0, "
"batch 1 → stream 1, round-robin). `tokio::spawn` hands the future to the "
"Tokio runtime."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:440
msgid ""
"On the first poll, the pipeline's `execute()` submits all GPU work to the "
"assigned stream and registers a `cuLaunchHostFunc` callback. The future "
"returns `Poll::Pending`. When the GPU finishes, the callback wakes the task. "
"No host thread spins."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:445
msgid ""
"    for (i, handle) in handles.into_iter().enumerate() {\n"
"        let result: Vec<f32> = handle.await.expect(\"Tokio task "
"panicked\")?;\n"
"        let all_non_negative = result.iter().all(|&v| v >= 0.0);\n"
"        println!(\"Batch {}: {} elements, first 8 = {:?}{}\",\n"
"            i, result.len(), &result[..8.min(result.len())],\n"
"            if all_non_negative { \" [ReLU OK]\" } else { \" [ReLU "
"FAILED]\" }\n"
"        );\n"
"    }\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../projects/async-mlp-pipeline.md:456
msgid ""
"The ReLU sanity check is not deep learning validation — it just confirms "
"that the activation function ran. Every output should be non-negative. If "
"you see `[ReLU FAILED]`, something upstream is very wrong."
msgstr ""

